$$PQ = \sqrt {{{(4 - 3)}^2} + {{(5 - 2)}^2}{{(2 - 4)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {{{(1)}^2} + {{(3)}^2} + {{( - 2)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {1 + 9 + 4}  = \sqrt {14} $$<br><br>$$QR = \sqrt {{{(5 - 4)}^2} + {{(8 - 5)}^2} + {{(0 - 2)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {{{(1)}^2} + {{(3)}^2} + {{( - 2)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {1 + 9 + 4}  = \sqrt {14} $$<br><br>$$RS = \sqrt {{{(2 - 5)}^2} + {{( - 1 - 8)}^2} + {{(6 - 0)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {{{( - 3)}^2} + {{( - 9)}^2} + {{(6)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {9 + 81 + 36}  = \sqrt {126} $$<br><br>and $$PS = \sqrt {{{(2 - 3)}^2} + {{( - 1 - 2)}^2} + {{(6 - 4)}^2}} $$<br><br>$$ = \sqrt {1 + 9 - 4}  = \sqrt {14} $$<br><br>Since, PQ $$\ne$$ RS<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ Given points are not vertices of a rhombus.<br><br>Now, direction ratios of PQ are 4 $$-$$ 3, 5 $$-$$ 2, 2 $$-$$ 4 i.e. 1, 3, $$-$$<br><br>direction ratios of PR are 5 $$-$$ 3, 8 $$-$$ 2, 0 $$-$$ 4, i.e. 2, 6, $$-$$4<br><br>direction ratios of PS are 2 $$-$$ 3, $$-$$ 1 $$-$$ 2, 6 $$-$$ 4 i.e. $$-$$1, $$-$$3, 2<br><br>$$\left| {PQ} \right| = \sqrt {1 + 9 + 4}  = \sqrt {14} $$<br><br>$$\left| {PQ} \right| = \sqrt {4 + 36 + 16}  = \sqrt {56}  = 2\sqrt {14} $$<br><br>$$\left| {PS} \right| = \sqrt {1 + 9 + 4}  = \sqrt {14} $$<br><br>$$\therefore$$ $$\left| {PQ} \right| = n\left| {PR} \right|$$ but $$\left| {PQ} \right| \ne m\left| {PS} \right|$$<br><br>So, these points are not collinear.<br><br>Given, points P, Q, R and S are coplanar if PQ, PR and PS are coplanar<br><br>i.e. $$[PQ\,PR\,PS] = 0$$<br><br>Here, $$\left| {\matrix{
   1 &amp; 3 &amp; { - 2}  \cr 
   2 &amp; 6 &amp; { - 4}  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; { - 3} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right| = ( - 1)\left| {\matrix{
   { - 1} &amp; { - 3} &amp; 2  \cr 
   2 &amp; 6 &amp; { - 4}  \cr 
   { - 1} &amp; { - 3} &amp; 2  \cr 

 } } \right|$$ = 0 (since R<sub>1</sub> and R<sub>3</sub> are identical)<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ PR, PQ and PS are coplanar<br><br>$$\Rightarrow$$ P, Q, R and S are coplanar.

